  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions is complex and has evolved significantly over time:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Roots can be traced back to efforts to combat organized crime in the early 20th century\n- Initial focus was on preventing criminal proceeds from being integrated into legitimate financial systems\n\n2. Key Milestones:\n- 1970 Bank Secrecy Act (US) - First major legislation requiring financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- 1986 Money Laundering Control Act (US) - Criminalized money laundering as a specific federal crime\n- 1989 Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established - Created international standards for combating money laundering\n\n3. International Development:\n- 1988 UN Vienna Convention addressed money laundering related to drug trafficking\n- 1990s saw increasing global cooperation and standardization of anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n- Post-9/11 regulations expanded to include counterterrorism financing\n\n4. Modern Legal Framework:\n- Comprehensive international regulatory regime\n- Mandatory reporting requirements\n- Enhanced due diligence processes\n- Significant criminal and civil penalties for non-compliance\n\nThe legal framework continues to evolve with technological developments and emerging financial practices.",
